<div id="content">
<h1 class="title">Project 2: Review</h1>
<p>
Well I'm 5 days late for this blog post, and I still don't have a great amount
of time. Fortunately there isn't a whole lot to write for this one.
</p>

<p>
I haven't worked much on sclip since the last blog post. The only new thing to
mention, I think, is the tiny little discord bot I made for interacting with
sclip from discord.
</p>

<p>
Disappointingly, my friends and I have not used sclip all that much. I think the
discord bot interface is simple enough, but there is definitely something to be
said for bots which are just accessible at all times. If sclip were
automatically available at any time, I feel that it would be more popular.
</p>

<p>
I'll also use this post to discuss the next project.
</p>

<div id="outline-container-org7fdec7a" class="outline-2">
<h2 id="org7fdec7a"><span class="section-number-2">1</span> Next Project</h2>
<div class="outline-text-2" id="text-1">
<p>
This last Summer I started getting into some of the older computers I used when
I was younger. I had a lot of fun looking at the files and games I had played in
my childhood, and I felt especially nostalgic for Otto Matic on the iMac
G4. I've always liked the idea of modifying games, so I got the idea to try
reverse engineering Otto Matic, so that I could play with it again. At the time
I was lacking some important information about linking, assembly, etc. but I at
least got to the point of playing with the Ghidra decompiler and even mostly
reverse engineering the special file format the game used for 3D
models. Although that really wasn't so much reverse engineering, as it was
finding and a book and some accompanying code by Brian Greenstone about his file
format. It was still pretty fun though.
</p>

<p>
Anyway I now know understand more about the fundamentals that might help with
reverse engineering, so I'll try this again. But I originally set out to make 12
useful things, and reverse engineering one game won't really be that useful to
anyone. So instead I'll try to learn a bit more about reversing in general in
another way.
</p>

<p>
I was frustrated by the interface to Ghidra I was using over the summer. Of
course, I didn't really understand the program itself, but my real issue was
with just doing code-related things outside of Emacs. So I'll make a tool for
reverse engineering in Emacs. That's not a very specific idea though.
</p>

<p>
Around the time I was looking at Ghidra I also saw Radare2. It looks like an
excellent program but I ended up neglecting it due to what I had already
invested into Ghidra. Radare2, though, is a much simpler and unix-y tool. And as
a relatively simple tool, it makes sense to extend it just by creating an
interface to it. So that is my more concrete idea. I will make an Emacs mode for
interacting with Radare2.
</p>

<p>
Magit is an incredible Emacs interface to Git, and the library that magit uses
for command interaction (transient.el) is available for use. So that's what I'll
do. I'll make a magit-inspired interface to Radare2 for Emacs.
</p>
</div>
</div>

<div id="outline-container-org3ad68dc" class="outline-2">
<h2 id="org3ad68dc"><span class="section-number-2">2</span> Bonus Project</h2>
<div class="outline-text-2" id="text-2">
<p>
I have two concerns. That project is probably not realistically doable within
this next month, and I've been sometimes annoyed with being completely dedicated
to a single project. It's kind of nice to bounce between a few things. So I'll
have a backup project.
</p>

<p>
I think Canvas is an okay tool for learning management. It's not perfect and can
be easily misused by some professors, but it's usually alright. Still, it's a very
slow interface.
</p>

<p>
This semester I've been working a lot in Ruby for one of my classes. It's not
the coolest language but it's pretty fun for small stuff. So I've decided to
make a little Ruby script for collecting information from Canvas through their
API. I'm pretty confident that at least this can be done even with finals this
month. The other project is a little lofty but I can at least learn some
interesting things from it.
</p>
</div>
</div>
</div>
